The paper deals with fundamental problems in computational geometry, such as Closest Pair, Diameter, and Minimum Spanning Tree, which are typically studied in the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category. The paper also uses techniques from data structures (cs.DS), complexity theory (cs.CC), discrete mathematics (cs.DM), and numerical analysis (cs.NA) to prove lower bounds for these problems. Additionally, the paper mentions a reduction from SAT, which is a problem in theoretical computer science (cs.THE), but this is not the main focus of the paper. Therefore, cs.CG is the most likely sub-category, followed by cs.DS, cs.CC, cs.DM, and cs.NA.
